For today’s lab we are going to explore the non-stationary relationship between the elevation of the properties that have sold since 2005 and their selling price. We expect that homes at lower elevations will be worth more because they are generally closer to the coast, but we will also explore an interaction with time to see if there hase been a noticable shift in value over our study period (2005-2017) due to Sea Level Rise and increased tidal flooding.


First, let’s set our working directory for any files we may write from R….


knitr::opts_chunk$set(

    message = TRUE,
    warning = TRUE
)

To begin, I am going to require the RPostgres package and read in the prop_val_sample_oc table from our lab4 schema to measure the value of the home at the point of sale and at the baseline year of 2005. Next, I want to read in the mhhw_slosh_sample table from the lab6 schema to measure the inundation levels from the hurricane scenarios and the difference between the water table at high tide and the elevation of the home. Finally, I want to read in the oc_assessor data from the lab7 schema (setup tonight with the file I gave you) to measure a selected set of housing characteristics as pricing controls for our model.


require(RPostgres)

Next, I am going to explore the ordering of the id variables for the oc_prop_flood and the oc_sale_data to make sure that they are in the same order as when we created them (they are) and then use the cbind function to create a new object oc_full by binding the two together column-wise. When I explore the data I can see that, at least in my case, the hurricane scenarios still have 99.9 to represent no inundation so I am going recode that to 0 for the entire oc_full object anywhere 99.9 exists. You want to be careful with this approach as it could change other variables ==99.9 to 0 as well, but in our case its fine for this set of data. Finally, because GWR models can not handle missing data, I am going to recode the missing values for the baseline 2005 price (samp_pr05) to the average for that variable (mean = 190.76477).

Now let’s require the sp package and convert our oc_full object and the oc_assessor object to a SpatialPointsDataFrame by setting x+y as the spatial coordinates via the coordinates function and projecting the CRS to 4269 via the proj4string function. I’m going to plot them both here to make sure they look reasonable. As you can see from the plot (and the object size in the environment) the oc_assessor data contains information for many more cases than we have sales data for… so let’s use the merge function to join the two object’s dataframes by the common fsid id variable. We now have a new object (oc_join) that represents the sales data, the risk of flooding, and the home characteristics for all recent sales in Ocean City, MD.


require(sp)
coordinates(oc_full)=~x+y
proj4string(oc_full)=CRS("+init=epsg:4269")
plot(oc_full)

coordinates(oc_assessor)=~x+y
proj4string(oc_assessor)=CRS("+init=epsg:4269")
plot(oc_assessor)

oc_join <- merge(oc_full@data, oc_assessor@data, by="fsid")

For today’s lab we are going to explore the non-stationarity of relationships associated with risk of flooding from tidal events (operationalized by elevation vs. water table) and the trend in home sales over our study period. To do that, we need to require the spgwr package, but first lets also explore the relationships as a linear function using lm. In the first model, I am just going to add the home characteristics as a “control model”. From this first model and in relation to the price per square foot at sale (pr_sq_ft), it appears that the size of the property (arealotacres) is positively associated with price, the size of the building (areabuilding) is negatively associated with price, the year the property was built (yearbuilt) is positively associated with price, the number of units in the property (unitscount) is positively assocaited with price, and single family home status (singfam) is negatively associated with price. With just property characteristics in the model, the R-Square indicates that only about 2% of the variation in sale price can be accounted for.


######GWR model
#install.packages("spgwr")
library(spgwr)

names(oc_join)
##  [1] "fsid"          "id.x"          "pr_sq_ft"      "saleyear"     
##  [5] "samp_pr05"     "geom"          "id.1"          "geom.1"       
##  [9] "c1_high"       "c2_high"       "c3_high"       "c4_high"      
## [13] "elev_water"    "id.y"          "tractfp"       "arealotacres" 
## [17] "areabuilding"  "bedroomscount" "yearbuilt"     "unitscount"   
## [21] "beachprox"     "fld_zone"      "near_golf"     "singfam"
lm_homechar <- lm(pr_sq_ft ~ arealotacres + areabuilding +
           yearbuilt + unitscount + singfam, data=oc_join)
summary(lm_homechar)

The second model adds to the pricing controls, information about the 2005 baseline price (samp_pr2005), a neighborhood control (factor(tractfp)) a flood zone control (factor(fld_zone)), and the difference between the high tide water table and the elvation of the property (elev_water). The results indicate that, controlling for the neighborhood differences and the flood zone delination, the 2005 market value is positively associated with later sale price and higher the elevation in relation to the high tide water table is negatively associated with sale price. This last finding is directly related to our research question and indicates that homes at higher elevations sell for less. In general, these would be home further from the coast and at less risk of flooding, but also in less desirable areas relative to the lower elevation coastal properties.


lm_flood <- lm(pr_sq_ft ~ arealotacres + areabuilding +
                 yearbuilt + unitscount + singfam + 
                 samp_pr05 + factor(tractfp) + factor(fld_zone) + 
                 elev_water, data=oc_join)

To the results to this point have not allowed us to uncover any kind of pricing discount or penalty associated with being a risk of flooding over time period. To tease out that result, we need to produce an interaction of assocaited with sale price as a function of the effect of elevation on sale price over time. To do this, we first have to create the time variable yr_vs_start as an indicator of the number of years since the baseline of our study period. Next, we have to introduce this variable into the regression model as both a main effect (yr_vs_start) and as an interaction with the elevation variable (elev_water:yr_vs_start). The results indicate that, controlling for everything else in the model, the number of year since 2005 variable is negatively associated with sale price and the effect of elevation over that time period is positively associated with sale price. This later is important to our research, because it indicates that over the study period there has been a shift towards homes at higher elevations with each foot of additional elevation being worth three cents on the dollar. Ultimately, this particular model does not allow us to test the actual mechanisms driving the preference for higher elevation homes, but we can make some assumptions assocaited with the increased tidal flooding caused by sea-level rise and the awareness of the community to the issue. This final model also accounts for about 25% if the variation in sale price over this time period per the R-Square.


oc_join$yr_vs_start <- oc_join$saleyear-2005

lm_floodtime <- lm(pr_sq_ft ~ arealotacres + areabuilding +
                     yearbuilt + unitscount + samp_pr05 + 
                     factor(tractfp) + factor(fld_zone) + elev_water +
                     yr_vs_start + elev_water:yr_vs_start, data=oc_join)
summary(lm_floodtime)

Now that we understand the general relationships, let’s see if these relationships are non-stationary per a GWR model of the same specification as the final model. The first thing we have to do is re-convert the data to a SpatialPointsDataFrame. To do this, I added ‘x’ and ‘y’ from one of our original files using the merge function and joining on the unique fsid variable, then assigned the coordinates and projected the spatial object.


oc_xy <- oc_sale_data[,c("fsid","x","y")]
oc_xy <- subset(oc_xy,!duplicated(fsid))
oc_join <- merge(oc_join,oc_xy,by="fsid")


coordinates(oc_join)=~x+y
proj4string(oc_join)=CRS("+init=epsg:4269")
plot(oc_join)


To obtain the optimal bandwidth for the GWR model, we can use the gwr.sel function applied to the same full regression model and set the weighting scheme equal to Gaussian (gweight=gwr.Gauss). I also set verbose=TRUE so that I could wath the progress as the function selected the optimal bandwidth.


bwG <- gwr.sel(pr_sq_ft ~ arealotacres + areabuilding +
                 yearbuilt + unitscount + samp_pr05 + factor(tractfp) +
                 factor(fld_zone) + elev_water + yr_vs_start +

               gweight=gwr.Gauss, verbose=TRUE)

Once the bandwidth has been chose, we can estimate our GWR model with the bandwidth argument being equal to that bandwidth object we created bwG. However, the GWR function does not recognize traditional interaction approaches so we need to hard code the elevation by year since sale interaction to create a new variable elv_wat_yr. After we do that, we can estimate the GWR model and save the results to a new object (gwrG).


oc_join$elv_wat_yr <- oc_join$elev_water*oc_join$yr_vs_start

gwrG <- gwr(pr_sq_ft ~ arealotacres + areabuilding + 
              yearbuilt + unitscount + samp_pr05 + factor(tractfp) +
              factor(fld_zone) + elev_water + yr_vs_start + 
              elv_wat_yr, data=oc_join, 
            bandwidth=bwG, gweight=gwr.Gauss)


Looking at the rsults of the gwrG output, we can see that there are a nested set of tables and objects…. we are intersted in the model results in the SDF table. In particular, we are interested in the geographically varying model fit (local R2), the geographically varying residuals (gwr.e), the geographic variation in the relationship between elevation and sale price (elev_water), and the geographic variation in the relationship between elevation and sale price over the study period (elv_wat_yr). In each of the plots, we can see significant variation in model fit and the effect of elevation (both as a main effect and in interaction form), however we don’t see a lot of variation in residuals which is a product of the better fitting local models.

Finally, I want to map these results using GGplot so I require the ggplot2 package. Also, to map the data I must also conver the data to a dataframe which I do with the as.data.frame function to convert the gwrG$SDF table to create the gwr_reslts object. One thing to note is that when using GGplot in the plotting points (in relation to polygons) you don’t have to fortify the file. The first object I create is a map of just the points to make sure that I have the data setup properly. To create the map, I use an empty ggplot() function + the geom_point function with the map data and aesthetics (aes) set to map the points from the gw_results object by longitude (x) and latitude (y).


require(ggplot2)
gwr_results <- as.data.frame(gwrG$SDF)


map <- ggplot() + geom_point(data=gwr_results, 
             aes(x=x, y=y), 
             color="red")
map


Since the data are set up properly to map, I am going to clean up the image by mapping the same object, with the same latitude and longitude, but specifying that this map vary the colors of the points by the variation in model fit (color = localR2). Futhermore, I want to set the labels of the x-axis and y-axis to empty (x="", y="") and set the title of the plot to Variation in Local R-Square. In the next chunk of code, I am removing the axis tick marks and text on both axes and adjusting the plot title to be bold faced, in the middle of the plot horizontally (hjust=0.5), at the bottom of the plot vertically (vjust=-132), and of font size 12 (size=12). In terms of the legend, I added the title “Model Fit” and the color scheme to range from light beige to dark red (colours=c( "#f9f3c2","#660000")). Finally, I placed the legend in the bottom right had corner (legend.position = c(0.90,0.23)) and set the text of both the legend title and the scale text to font size 7.


map2 <- ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data=gwr_results, aes(x=x, y=y, color=localR2)) +
  labs(x="", y="", title = "Variation in Local R-Square") +
  theme(axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),axis.text.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),axis.text.x = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(face="bold", hjust=0.5, vjust=-132, size=12)) +
  scale_colour_gradientn("Model\nFit", 
                         colours=c( "#f9f3c2","#660000")) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.90,0.23),
        legend.text=element_text(size=7),
        legend.title=element_text(size=7))
